Certainly! Below is a JavaScript function that configures and displays a modal dialog using AngularJS. This function assumes you have a directive or service that handles the modal logic.

```javascript
angular.module('myApp', [])
  .controller('MyController', function($scope) {
    $scope.openModal = function(content, buttonClass) {
      // Create a modal element
      var modal = document.createElement('div');
      modal.className = 'modal';
      modal.innerHTML = `
        <div class="modal-content">
          <span class="close">&times;</span>
          <p>${content}</p>
        </div>
      `;

      // Add the modal to the body
      document.body.appendChild(modal);

      // Get the <span> element that closes the modal
      var span = document.getElementsByClassName("close")[0];

      // When the user clicks on <span> (x), close the modal
      span.onclick = function() {
        modal.style.display = "none";
      }

      // When the user clicks anywhere outside of the modal, close it
      window.onclick = function(event) {
        if (event.target == modal) {
          modal.style.display = "none";
        }
      }

      // Add the button class to the modal
      modal.getElementsByClassName("modal-content")[0].classList.add(buttonClass);
    };
  });
```

### Explanation:
- **AngularJS Module and Controller**: The code defines an AngularJS module named `myApp` and a controller `MyController`.
- **openModal Function**: This function takes two parameters: `content` (the text to display in the modal) and `buttonClass` (the class to apply to the button).
- **Modal Creation**: It creates a `div` element with the class `modal` and sets its inner HTML to include the content and a close button.
- **Appending to Body**: The modal is appended to the `body` of the document.
- **Close Functionality**: The close button is set to hide the modal when clicked, and the modal is hidden when clicked outside of it.
- **Button Class**: The function adds the specified `buttonClass` to the modal content to style the button as needed.

### Usage:
To use this function, you can call it from a controller method, passing the desired content and button class. For example:

```javascript
$scope.openModal("This is a custom modal dialog.", "custom-button-class");
```

This will display a modal with the specified content and button class.

